      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i think i might be able to check the capacitor myself if i buy a replacement part. do i need special tools to swap it out or is it pretty straight forward? also it's making this weird intermittent buzzing sound like it's trying to start but then stopping. is that normal for a bad capacitor?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can definitely check the capacitor yourself, and while it doesn't require a degree in electrical engineering, it does require a specific tool called a multimeter to test the capacitance before you even unscrew the old one. Swapping it out is generally straightforward for most residential units, but you must be careful because the capacitor can still hold a deadly charge even after the power is off, so you need to discharge it first. The intermittent buzzing sound you're describing is actually a very strong indicator that the capacitor is indeed failing; it's trying to push the motor but can't build enough voltage to keep it running, so it cycles on and off. If you decide to proceed, always wear safety glasses and gloves, and if you feel any uncertainty, it's better to call a professional than to risk getting shocked by a live circuit.",
