    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It is completely normal for the AC to act up like that because the capacitor is essentially a battery that stores energy to give the motor a quick burst of power to start; when it degrades, it can't hold that charge, so the motor gets a little bit of juice, tries to spin, fails, and then the system cuts power to protect itself, creating that random on-and-off behavior. This failure is usually caused by age, heat cycles, or just a natural breakdown of the internal chemical components over time, rather than some magical electricity glitch. While the electricity itself isn't \"weird,\" the sudden loss of power is a safety feature trying to prevent the motor from burning out completely. If you are feeling nervous about the electrical aspect, it is often wiser to have a technician handle it, as they know how to safely discharge the capacitor and test the wiring without the risk of a surprise shock. Even if you do proceed, remember that working on high-voltage equipment requires respect and caution, so don't rush it.",
